<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1303,2012]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis box="[199,300,1304,1327]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">Structure</emphasis>
. Head elongate ovoid, dorsally distinctly convex, partly setose, finely granular, ventrally flattish, slightly longer than its width, with deep transverse sulcus between eyes. A fine, longitudinal, median sulcus present in front of transverse sulcus, meeting transverse sulcus. Anteocular area narrowed considerably, slightly declivous; post-ocular area slightly narrowed, gently constricted near middle and tumescent above. Clypeus prominently raised; mandibular plates shorter than clypeus. Antenniferous tubercles large, situated on top of head, slightly divergent (
<figureCitation box="[275,360,1483,1508]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,409,1948]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 14. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov. 8, Thoracic sterna; 9, abdominal sternites in female; 10, pygophore in ventral view; 11, head in dorsal view; 12, head, pronotum and scutellum; 13, prothorax in ventrolateral view, 14, hemelytra." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Fig. 
<number box="[331,360,1484,1508]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
). Eyes moderately large, semi-globular, coarsely granular. Antennae with antennomeres very thin. Labium extending up to fore coxae, moderately stout; first visible segment not extending up to anterior border of eye; second visible segment reaching almost up to base of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1303,2012]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Pronotum long; anterior lobe more or less smooth, covered with a few fine setae, convex in anterior half, flattened in posterior half, distinct from posterior lobe by constriction, slightly longer than posterior lobe, and with lateral margins almost parallel-sided, anterior margin concave and anterior angles tubercular and projecting outward; posterior lobe bell-shaped, finely punctured and rugulose, sloping forward, broader than anterior lobe, humeral angles bluntly triangular and posterior margin concave (
<figureCitation box="[883,966,1735,1760]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,409,1948]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 14. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov. 8, Thoracic sterna; 9, abdominal sternites in female; 10, pygophore in ventral view; 11, head in dorsal view; 12, head, pronotum and scutellum; 13, prothorax in ventrolateral view, 14, hemelytra." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Fig. 
<number box="[935,966,1736,1760]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Prosternum slightly concave. Scutellum sub-triangular, with lateral borders gently sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[717,800,1771,1796]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,409,1948]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 14. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov. 8, Thoracic sterna; 9, abdominal sternites in female; 10, pygophore in ventral view; 11, head in dorsal view; 12, head, pronotum and scutellum; 13, prothorax in ventrolateral view, 14, hemelytra." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Fig. 
<number box="[769,800,1772,1796]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1303,2012]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Hemelytra fully covering abdomen, surpassing apex of abdomen, its venation more or less typical (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1422,1807,1832]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 14" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,409,1948]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 14. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov. 8, Thoracic sterna; 9, abdominal sternites in female; 10, pygophore in ventral view; 11, head in dorsal view; 12, head, pronotum and scutellum; 13, prothorax in ventrolateral view, 14, hemelytra." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266810/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1422,1808,1832]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
); hind wings small, very thin, delicate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1303,2012]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="369" pageId="3" pageNumber="368">
Fore legs with coxa much longer than its width, projecting in front of head; trochanter short; femur longer than coxa, almost as long as tibia and tarsus combined, ventrally with 
<number box="[896,910,1916,1940]" pageId="3" pageNumber="368" value="2.0">2</number>
rows of spine-like setae; anteroventral (inner) row slightly curved at base, starting far from base of femur; posteroventral (outer) row starting at base of femur; basal setae somewhat stronger and longer than remaining setae; tibia shorter but more than half as long as femur, ventrally with slightly thick setae bent and pointed towards apex, and dorsally with very fine setae; tarsus with fine curved claw at tip (
<figureCitation box="[366,475,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1567,1589]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,625,1545]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1435,625,1546]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 7. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., fore leg. 5, Femur, tibia and tarsus showing color and relative proportions; 6, tarsus showing dark, longest basal segment; 7, tibia showing a ventral row of adpressed dark spines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266809/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Figs. 
<number box="[429,475,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Mid and hind legs very thin, very long; mid femur extending beyond abdominal apex by 
<quantity box="[1210,1299,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
; hind femur surpassing abdominal apex by almost 
<quantity box="[578,646,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Male genitalia: Pygophore about 
<quantity box="[573,659,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long, ventrally convex, dorsally flat (
<figureCitation box="[1081,1218,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1950,1972]" captionTargetBox="[189,1385,193,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[189,1387,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 18. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., male genitalia. 15, pygophore in dorsal view; 16, pygophore in lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, phallus in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266811/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Figs. 15, 16</figureCitation>
). Parameres visible outside, curved apically as in other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[661,762,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Bagauda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[661,762,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Bagauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, slightly swollen around middle, with beak-like apex, setose (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1950,1972]" captionTargetBox="[189,1385,193,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[189,1387,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 18. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., male genitalia. 15, pygophore in dorsal view; 16, pygophore in lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, phallus in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266811/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,243,368,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Phallus weakly sclerotized; endosoma with very fine spines and spinules of complex arrangement (
<figureCitation captionStart-0="FIGURES 15 – 18" captionStart-1="FIGURES 19 – 22" captionStartId-0="6.[151,264,1950,1972]" captionStartId-1="7.[151,264,1261,1283]" captionTargetBox-0="[189,1385,193,1920]" captionTargetBox-1="[172,1413,194,1235]" captionTargetId-0="figure@6.[189,1387,193,1921]" captionTargetId-1="figure@7.[170,1418,179,1246]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="7" captionText-0="FIGURES 15 – 18. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., male genitalia. 15, pygophore in dorsal view; 16, pygophore in lateral view; 17, paramere; 18, phallus in lateral view." captionText-1="FIGURES 19 – 22. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., phallus and female terminalia. 19, Phallus in dorsal view; 20, same in lateral view; 21, same in ventral view; 22, female genital segments in dorsal view; 23, same in ventral view." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/266811/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/266812/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Figs. 
<number box="[151,225,404,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="19.5" valueMax="21.0" valueMin="18.0">18–21</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" box="[199,1387,439,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Female genitalia: genital segments in dorsal and ventral views, respectively, are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[1207,1297,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 22" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1261,1283]" captionTargetBox="[172,1413,194,1235]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[170,1418,179,1246]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 22. Bagauda ernstmayri sp. nov., phallus and female terminalia. 19, Phallus in dorsal view; 20, same in lateral view; 21, same in ventral view; 22, female genital segments in dorsal view; 23, same in ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/266812/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Figs. 
<number box="[1269,1297,440,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<number box="[1352,1383,440,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="23.0">23</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,476,501]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the late Ernst Mayr, a most respected theorist of systematic zoology and a foremost evolutionary biologist of the 
<number box="[649,677,511,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" value="20.0">20</number>
th Century.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1227,548,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,573]" box="[199,1227,548,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,548,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Distribution.</emphasis>
Presently known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[713,761,549,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">type</typeStatus>
locality-Satara, Maharashtra State, 
<collectingCountry box="[1162,1223,548,573]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
